#ArtistInterventions: James Turrell's 2013 exhibition focused on the artist's groundbreaking explorations of perception, light, color, and space, with special attention to the role of site-specificity in his practice. At its center was "Aten Reign" (2013), a major new project that recast the museum's rotunda as a volume filled with shifting artificial and natural light. Suspended in the center of the museum was a massive assembly, which held daylight from the museum's oculus in its deepest central layer. Using a series of interlocking cones lined with LED fixtures, this core of daylight was surrounded by five elliptical rings of shifting, colored light that echoed the banded pattern of the museum's ramps. Reorienting visitors' experiences of the rotunda from the ramps to the main floor, "Aten Reign" gave form to the air and light occupying the museum's central void, proposing an entirely new experience of the building and fostering what Turrell calls "an architecture of space created with light."
__
Since opening in 1959, our Frank Lloyd Wright-designed museum has served as inspiration for invention, challenging artists and architects to react to its eccentric, organic design. Follow #Guggenheim60 to discover more artist interventions during our 60th anniversary year!

Photo: David Heald

On this day in 1979, Peggy Guggenheim, patron of 20th-century art, passed away. This year the @guggenheim_venice is commemorating two anniversaries—70 years since Peggy moved to Palazzo Venier dei Leoni, and 40 years since her passing—with the exhibition “Peggy Guggenheim: The Last Dogaressa," on view though January 27, 2020. 
__
Photo: Tony Vaccaro (@tonyvaccarophotographer) #LastDogaressa #PeggyGuggenheimCollection #Guggenheim

#WorkoftheWeek: Georges Mathieu adopted a gestural abstract style distinguished by his predominant use of calligraphic signs and unusually rapid mode of painting. In “Untitled” (1959), the entangled, swirling lines were applied directly onto the surface of the canvas from a paint tube. From the early 1950s, Mathieu began to make art before large public audiences, documenting his performative actions through photography and film.
__
“Untitled” (1959), on view in #ArtisticLicense, is being exhibited at the Guggenheim Museum in New York for the first time. Plan your visit at guggenheim.org/artisticlicense.
#GeorgesMattieu #Guggenheim

#ArtistInterventions: In 2013 the Guggenheim and @JapanSociety_nyc presented “SANBASO, divine dance” in conjunction with the exhibition “Gutai: Splendid Playground.” Internationally renowned artist Hiroshi Sugimoto and acclaimed kyogen actor Mansai Nomura created the site-specific version of “Sanbaso,” one of the oldest dance pieces in the highly stylized stage art traditions of noh and kyogen, which date back more than six hundred years. With its origins in an ancient ritual ceremony, Sanbaso is a prayer to the gods for a bountiful harvest and is traditionally performed by a kyogen actor. This production was conceived a tribute to the stage performance “Ultramodern Sanbaso” (1957) by Shiraga Kazuo, one of the leading figures of Japan’s avant-garde Gutai movement. 
__

Happy birthday to pioneer of abstract art and theorist Vasily Kandinsky, born on this day in 1866. Although known for his groundbreaking abstract experiments in painting, Kandinsky’s early paintings capture his days as a representational artist, including "Amsterdam—View From The Window," 1904 (pictured here), which is on view in #ArtisticLicense through January 12.

Kandinsky has been linked to the history of the Guggenheim more than any other 20th century painter. Hilla Rebay—artist, art advisor, and the museum’s first director—was particularly inspired by his work and writing. As a result, the Guggenheim collection contains more than 150 works by this single artist. 
__
#Guggenheim #GuggenheimCollection #Kandinsky

Enjoy #NationalCupcakeDay with a Guggenheim fun fact: the "inverted cupcake" was one of many nicknames given to the museum when it first opened in 1959. 🧁 Frank Lloyd Wright's spiral building was inspired by ancient ziggurats, but Wright turned the shape upside down to express expansive possibility: the spiral could theoretically go on infinitely toward the sky. 
__
Photo: Neta Rigatos
#Guggenheim #FrankLloydWright #cupcakes

Today's #FrankLloydWrightFridays illustration is by @saeed.rostambakhsh—"The Guggenheim is a limitless place in which you can be everywhere and anywhere when you are standing in it. The round shapes are symbols of femininity that have broken the walls." #Guggenheim #Guggenheim60

“When you go to something as vast as the Guggenheim’s collection is, you start to see patterns.”—Richard Prince

When preparing for his #ArtisticLicense presentation, Prince discovered a surprising number of commonalities among paintings made between the 1940s and early 1960s, many created by lesser-known Abstract Expressionist artists. 📣 Hear Prince discuss his selections on Tuesday, December 17, 6:30 pm. Tickets include same-day museum admission! Learn more at guggenheim.org/artisticlicense.
__
#RichardPrince #Guggenheim

#GuessTheArtist answer: Paul Cézanne, “Man with Crossed Arms” (1899). In this work, the strangely distorted view of the sitter—his right eye is depicted as if glimpsed from below and the left as if seen from above—gives the painting a contemplative air. This portrait has come to be seen as a psychological study of quiet resignation and reserve—characteristics often attributed to Cézanne during the last decade of his life. 
#GuggenheimCollection #Guggenheim #PaulCézanne

#ArtistInterventions: As part of the 2013 exhibition “Gutai: Splendid Playground,” the Guggenheim commissioned Japanese artist Motonaga Sadamasa to recreate “Work (Water)” (1956/2011), which was first presented at an outdoor exhibition by the Gutai group—Japan's most significant postwar avant-garde movement. Conceptualized for the rotunda by the artist shortly before his death in 2011, the polyethylene tubes designed for industrial use were filled with brightly colored water and suspended between the ramps in open air. With light streaming down from the oculus high above, the work took on an experiential dimension, changing continuously as light flickered through and shadows moved across the spectrum of colors over the course of the day.
__

#WorkoftheWeek: In her staged photographs of miniature-scale interiors and toy figurines, @LaurieSimmons meditates on the intersections between fiction and reality, and considers prescribed forms of femininity. Her early black-and-white works from the 1970s capture the cinematic play of light and shadow on the detailed, retro decor of dollhouses, at once familiar and disorienting in scale. 
__
“Bathroom I (Oversize)” and “Bathroom II (Oversize)” (both 1976), on view in #ArtisticLicense, are being exhibited at the Guggenheim Museum for the first time. Plan your visit at guggenheim.org/artisticlicense.
#LaurieSimmons #Guggenheim

“The work that I’m interested in is work that pulls me in, that allows me to discover something about myself, to question, to ponder, to consider.”—@CarrieMaeWeems

For her #ArtisticLicense presentation, Weems restricted her selections to a predominantly black-and-white palette, in a metaphoric gesture that alludes to the relatively small number of artists of color from this period in the collection. 
Learn more at guggenheim.org/artisticlicense.
__
#CarrieMaeWeems #Guggenheim

Today's #FrankLloydWrightFridays drawing is by @yolahugo—“The Guggenheim is one of my favorite buildings in NYC, so I draw it often. This time, I represented the museum in a different way, just painting the shadows. The result of the dialogue between negative and positive parts suggests forms—there’s no need to outline them.”
